{:pack/id "security-baseline"
 :pack/name "Security Baseline Pack"
 :pack/version "2026.01.22"
 :pack/description "Security best practices for all code"
 :pack/author "miniforge-official"
 :pack/license "Apache-2.0"

 :pack/categories
 [{:category/id "510"
   :category/name "Secrets Management"
   :category/rules [:510-no-hardcoded-secrets
                    :511-no-secrets-in-logs]}
  {:category/id "520"
   :category/name "IAM Best Practices"
   :category/rules [:520-no-wildcard-actions]}]

 :pack/rules
 [;;============================================================================
  ;; Category 510: Secrets Management
  ;;============================================================================

  {:rule/id :510-no-hardcoded-secrets
   :rule/title "No hardcoded secrets"
   :rule/description "Secrets must not be hardcoded in source files"
   :rule/severity :critical
   :rule/category "510"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/*.clj" "**/*.cljc" "**/*.ts" "**/*.js"
                 "**/*.py" "**/*.tf" "**/*.yaml" "**/*.yml"
                 "**/*.json" "**/*.edn"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :patterns [;; API keys and tokens (generic)
               "(?i)(api[_-]?key|secret[_-]?key|access[_-]?token|auth[_-]?token)\\s*[:=]\\s*['\"][a-zA-Z0-9_-]{16,}['\"]"
               ;; AWS credentials
               "AKIA[0-9A-Z]{16}"
               "(?i)aws[_-]?secret[_-]?access[_-]?key\\s*[:=]\\s*['\"][^'\"]{40}['\"]"
               ;; Private keys
               "-----BEGIN (RSA |EC |DSA |OPENSSH )?PRIVATE KEY-----"
               ;; Bearer tokens
               "(?i)bearer\\s+[a-zA-Z0-9_-]{20,}"
               ;; Generic passwords in config
               "(?i)password\\s*[:=]\\s*['\"][^'\"]{8,}['\"]"
               ;; GitHub tokens
               "ghp_[a-zA-Z0-9]{36}"
               "gho_[a-zA-Z0-9]{36}"
               "ghu_[a-zA-Z0-9]{36}"
               "ghs_[a-zA-Z0-9]{36}"
               "ghr_[a-zA-Z0-9]{36}"
               ;; Slack tokens
               "xox[baprs]-[0-9a-zA-Z]{10,48}"
               ;; Stripe keys
               "sk_live_[0-9a-zA-Z]{24}"
               "rk_live_[0-9a-zA-Z]{24}"]}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "Never hardcode secrets in source code. Use one of these approaches:

    Environment variables (simplest):
    - Clojure: (System/getenv \"API_KEY\")
    - Python: os.environ.get('API_KEY')
    - TypeScript: process.env.API_KEY
    - Terraform: variable \"api_key\" { sensitive = true }

    Secrets manager (recommended for production):
    - AWS Secrets Manager
    - HashiCorp Vault
    - Google Secret Manager
    - Azure Key Vault

    Kubernetes secrets:
    - Mount as files: /var/secrets/api-key
    - Inject as env vars via secretKeyRef

    If you see what looks like a secret in code, flag it IMMEDIATELY:
    1. Do not commit the change
    2. If already committed, rotate the secret
    3. Use git-secrets or similar pre-commit hooks
    4. Check git history for exposed secrets

    Common false positives to ignore:
    - Example values in documentation (use 'xxx' or 'your-key-here')
    - Test fixtures with obviously fake values
    - Hash values (SHA256, MD5) that aren't secrets"

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :hard-halt
    :message "Possible hardcoded secret detected"
    :remediation "Remove secret from code. Use environment variable or secrets manager."}}

  {:rule/id :511-no-secrets-in-logs
   :rule/title "No secrets in log statements"
   :rule/description "Log statements must not include sensitive data"
   :rule/severity :critical
   :rule/category "510"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/*.clj" "**/*.cljc" "**/*.ts" "**/*.js" "**/*.py"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :patterns [;; Logging patterns with secret-like variable names
               "(?i)(log|logger|console)\\.(info|debug|warn|error|log).*\\b(password|secret|token|api[_-]?key|credentials?)\\b"
               ;; Clojure logging
               "(?i)\\(log/(info|debug|warn|error).*\\b(password|secret|token|api[_-]?key|credentials?)\\b"
               ;; Print statements (often used for debugging)
               "(?i)(println|print|printf|fmt\\.Print).*\\b(password|secret|token|api[_-]?key|credentials?)\\b"]}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "Secrets must never appear in logs. Logs are often:
    - Stored unencrypted
    - Accessible to many team members
    - Sent to third-party log aggregators
    - Retained for extended periods

    Common mistakes:
    - Logging full request/response bodies
    - Debug logging of configuration objects
    - Error messages that include credentials
    - Logging user input without sanitization

    Safe logging practices:
    1. Log only what's necessary for debugging
    2. Mask sensitive fields: 'api_key: ***REDACTED***'
    3. Use structured logging with explicit field lists
    4. Review log statements in code review

    Example of safe logging:
    (log/info \"API call completed\" {:user-id user-id :status status})
    NOT: (log/info \"API call\" {:config config})  ; config may contain secrets

    If you need to debug auth issues:
    - Log that a token was present/absent, not the token itself
    - Log token length or last 4 characters at most
    - Use request IDs to correlate without exposing data"

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :hard-halt
    :message "Possible secret in log statement: %s"
    :remediation "Remove sensitive data from log. Use redaction or omit entirely."}}

  ;;============================================================================
  ;; Category 520: IAM Best Practices
  ;;============================================================================

  {:rule/id :520-no-wildcard-actions
   :rule/title "No wildcard IAM actions"
   :rule/description "IAM policies must not use Action: '*'"
   :rule/severity :critical
   :rule/category "520"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/*.tf" "**/*.json"]
    :resource-patterns ["aws_iam_policy" "aws_iam_role_policy"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :patterns [;; JSON format
               "\"Action\"\\s*:\\s*\"\\*\""
               "\"Action\"\\s*:\\s*\\[\\s*\"\\*\"\\s*\\]"
               ;; HCL format
               "Action\\s*=\\s*\\[\\s*\"\\*\"\\s*\\]"
               "actions\\s*=\\s*\\[\\s*\"\\*\"\\s*\\]"
               ;; Also catch service wildcards
               "\"Action\"\\s*:\\s*\"[a-z0-9]+:\\*\""]}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "IAM policies must follow the principle of least privilege:

    WRONG:
    {
      \"Effect\": \"Allow\",
      \"Action\": \"*\",
      \"Resource\": \"*\"
    }

    RIGHT:
    {
      \"Effect\": \"Allow\",
      \"Action\": [
        \"s3:GetObject\",
        \"s3:PutObject\"
      ],
      \"Resource\": \"arn:aws:s3:::my-bucket/*\"
    }

    Guidelines:
    1. Specify exact actions needed (s3:GetObject, s3:PutObject)
    2. Never use Action: '*' (admin access)
    3. Scope resources to specific ARNs, not '*'
    4. Use conditions to further restrict access

    Service-level wildcards (e.g., s3:*) are also dangerous:
    - s3:* includes s3:DeleteBucket
    - ec2:* includes ec2:TerminateInstances
    - iam:* includes iam:CreateUser (privilege escalation)

    If broad access is truly needed:
    1. Document business justification
    2. Limit to specific resources/accounts
    3. Add time-based conditions if possible
    4. Get security team review
    5. Consider using AWS Organizations SCPs as guardrails"

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :hard-halt
    :message "IAM policy uses wildcard action"
    :remediation "Replace '*' with specific actions needed. Document if broad access required."}}]}
